"Katsikatsou M., Anestis A., Pörtner H.O., Kampouris T., Michaelidis B.","Field studies on the relation between the accumulation of heavy metals and metabolic and HSR in the bearded horse mussel Modiolus barbatus",2011,"Comparative Biochemistry and Physiology - C Toxicology and Pharmacology","153","1",,"133","140",,,10.1016/j.cbpc.2010.10.001,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-78649705559&partnerID=40&md5=68256d6f394e97de3732f77ec09414ae","Department of Zoology, School of Biology, Aristotle University of Thessaloniki, Thessaloniki 54124, Greece; Alfred-Wegener-Institut für Polar-und Meeresforschung, Ökophysiologie Mariner Tiere, Postfach 120161, D-27515 Bremerhaven, Germany; Department of Marine Science, School of the Environment, University of the Aegean, University Hill, 81100, Mytilene, Greece","Katsikatsou, M., Department of Zoology, School of Biology, Aristotle University of Thessaloniki, Thessaloniki 54124, Greece; Anestis, A., Department of Zoology, School of Biology, Aristotle University of Thessaloniki, Thessaloniki 54124, Greece; Pörtner, H.O., Alfred-Wegener-Institut für Polar-und Meeresforschung, Ökophysiologie Mariner Tiere, Postfach 120161, D-27515 Bremerhaven, Germany; Kampouris, T., Department of Marine Science, School of the Environment, University of the Aegean, University Hill, 81100, Mytilene, Greece; Michaelidis, B., Department of Zoology, School of Biology, Aristotle University of Thessaloniki, Thessaloniki 54124, Greece","The present study aims to examine whether the seasonal changes in the levels of heavy metals Cd and Pb in the gills of sublittoral mussel Modiolus barbatus from populations distributed in Thermaikos Gulf are correlated to seasonal molecular (Heat Shock Response) and metabolic stress responses of this species. Our results indicate a season effect in the accumulation of heavy metals in the gills of bivalves in the area of Thermaikos Gulf, possibly implicating biological (reproductive cycle), natural (rivers' flow) and anthropogenic factors. Among the members of heat shock proteins (Hsps) examined, inducible Hsp70 seemed to play a major cytoprotective role against toxicity of metals. However, bivalves' tolerance against heavy metals may decrease during warming, arising further questions for their survival in context of global warming. © 2010 Elsevier Inc.","Bivalves; Cd and Pb; Heavy metals; Hsps; Metabolism","cadmium; heat shock protein 70; heat shock protein 72; heat shock protein 90; lead; animal tissue; article; bioaccumulation; cell protection; controlled study; gill; greenhouse effect; heat shock response; metabolic stress; mussel; nonhuman; ovary cycle; priority journal; river; seasonal variation; warming; Animals; Cadmium; Environmental Monitoring; Gills; Heat-Shock Proteins; Heat-Shock Response; Lead; Metabolism; Metals, Heavy; Mytilidae; Seasons; Seawater; Water Pollutants, Chemical; Bivalvia; Equidae; Modiolus barbatus",,"cadmium, 22537-48-0, 7440-43-9; lead, 13966-28-4, 7439-92-1; Cadmium, 7440-43-9; Heat-Shock Proteins; Lead, 7439-92-1; Metals, Heavy; Water Pollutants, Chemical",,,,"Anestis, A., Lazou, A., Pörtner, H.O., Michaelidis, B., Behavioral, metabolic, and molecular stress responses of marine bivalve Mytilus galloprovincialis during long-term acclimation at increasing ambient temperature (2007) Am. J. Physiol. Regul. Integr. Comp. Physiol., 293, pp. 911-R921; Anestis, A., Pörtner, H.O., Lazou, A., Michaelidis, B., Metabolic and molecular stress responses of sublittoral bearded horse mussel Modiolus barbatus to warming sea water: Implications for vertical zonation (2008) J. Exp. Biol., 211, pp. 2889-2898; Astraldi, M., Bianchi, C.N., Gasparini, G.P., Morri, C., Climatic fluctuations, current variability and marine species distribution: A case study in the Ligurian Sea (north-west Mediterranean) (1995) Oceanol. Acta, 18, pp. 139-149; Béthoux, J.P., Gentili, B., Raunet, J., Tailliez, D., Warming trend in the western Mediterranean deep water (1990) Nature,